    "customer_segment"
]

campaign_columns = [

]

if all(col in customer_profiles.columns for col in required_columns) and \
   all(col in campaign_results.columns for col in campaign_columns):
    
    # Merge datasets on customer_id
    merged_data = pd.merge(customer_profiles, campaign_results, on='customer_id')
    
    # Calculate summary statistics
    avg_age = merged_data['age'].mean()
    income_distribution = merged_data['income_bracket'].value_counts(normalize=True)
    product_ownership = merged_data[['has_checking', 'has_savings', 'has_mortgage', 'has_auto_loan']].mean()
    campaign_response_rates = merged_data[['email_opened', 'clicked_offer', 'applied_for_card', 'card_activated']].mean()
    
    # Create subplots
    fig = make_subplots(
        rows=2, cols=2,

        specs=[[{"type": "xy"}, {"type": "xy"}], [{"type": "xy"}, {"type": "xy"}]]
    )
    
    # Add Average Age as a bar chart
    fig.add_trace(go.Bar(x=['Average Age'], y=[avg_age], name='Average Age'), row=1, col=1)
    
    # Add Income Distribution as a bar chart
    fig.add_trace(go.Bar(x=income_distribution.index, y=income_distribution.values, name='Income Distribution'), row=1, col=2)
    
    # Add Product Ownership as a bar chart
    fig.add_trace(go.Bar(x=product_ownership.index, y=product_ownership.values, name='Product Ownership'), row=2, col=1)
    
    # Add Campaign Response Rates as a bar chart
    fig.add_trace(go.Bar(x=campaign_response_rates.index, y=campaign_response_rates.values, name='Campaign Response Rates'), row=2, col=2)
    
    # Update layout
    fig.update_layout(template='plotly_white', showlegend=False)
    
    # Store the result
    result = {
        "average_age": avg_age,
        "income_distribution": income_distribution.to_dict(),
        "product_ownership": product_ownership.to_dict(),
        "campaign_response_rates": campaign_response_rates.to_dict()
    }

**Code:**
```python
# Load the datasets
customer_profiles = datasets['customer_profiles']
campaign_results = datasets['campaign_results']

# Verify required columns exist in both datasets
required_columns = ["customer_id", "age", "income_bracket", "num_products", "email_opened", 
                    "clicked_offer", "applied_for_card", "card_activated", 
                    "monthly_card_spend", "revenue_generated"]

if all(column in customer_profiles.columns for column in ["customer_id", "age", "income_bracket", "num_products"]) and \
   all(column in campaign_results.columns for column in ["customer_id", "email_opened", "clicked_offer", 
                                                         "applied_for_card", "card_activated", 
                                                         "monthly_card_spend", "revenue_generated"]):
    # Merge datasets on 'customer_id'
    merged_df = pd.merge(customer_profiles[['customer_id', 'age', 'income_bracket', 'num_products']],
                         campaign_results[['customer_id', 'email_opened', 'clicked_offer', 
                                           'applied_for_card', 'card_activated', 
                                           'monthly_card_spend', 'revenue_generated']],
                         on='customer_id', how='inner')

    # Calculate total revenue generated
    total_revenue = merged_df['revenue_generated'].sum()

    # Calculate conversion rates
    conversion_rates = {
        'email_opened_rate': merged_df['email_opened'].mean(),
        'clicked_offer_rate': merged_df['clicked_offer'].mean(),
        'applied_for_card_rate': merged_df['applied_for_card'].mean(),
        'card_activated_rate': merged_df['card_activated'].mean()
    }

    # Store results
    result = {
        'total_revenue': total_revenue,
        'conversion_rates': conversion_rates,
        'merged_data_shape': merged_df.shape
    }
else:
    result = "Required columns are missing in the datasets."
```
